Components, standard parts and materials for installation. 
1. The organisation shall establish procedures for the acceptance of components, standard parts and materials for installation to ensure that components, standard parts and materials are in a satisfactory condition and meet the applicable requirements of point (a). 
2. The procedures shall specify all of the following: 
(i) the persons in charge of the acceptance of components, standard parts and materials; 
(ii) the sources from which components, standard parts and materials may be accepted, and the verification to be carried out for their acceptance; 
(iii) the handling and storage of components, standard parts and materials; 
(iv) the cases where the EASA Form 1 or equivalent may not be available, and the way to control those cases. 
3. The organisation shall ensure that the components, standard parts and materials for installation are only installed on the aircraft or component when they are specified in the applicable maintenance data. 
4. The organisation shall keep records of the acceptance of components, standard parts and materials, and of the related conformity or airworthiness statements and release certificates.

Unsalvageable components. 
1. The organisation shall establish procedures to ensure that unsalvageable components are prevented from re-entering the component supply system, and that they are retained in a secure location under the control of the organisation until they are permanently deformed, mutilated or destroyed. 
2. ‘Unsalvageable components’ are components with no prospect of return to a serviceable condition, and may only be used for non-aviation purposes, such as training, research or other non-aviation applications. 
3. The following components shall be classified as unsalvageable components: 
(i) components with a non-repairable defect described in the applicable maintenance data; 
(ii) components that do not meet the specified design characteristics and cannot be brought into conformity with them; 
(iii) components for which the applicable maintenance data do not exist or are not made available to the organisation; 
(iv) components for which the required continued-airworthiness information is not available; 
(v) components that have been subjected to unacceptable modifications or that have been repaired in an unacceptable manner; 
(vi) components that have been removed from an aircraft that has been involved in a serious incident or accident, and for which the applicable competent authority has determined that they are unsalvageable. 
4. By derogation to point (1), the organisation may transfer the unsalvageable components to another organisation for training or research purposes without mutilation, provided that it has given notice thereof to the competent authority. That transfer shall be reflected in the records of the organisation and shall be documented in a way that allows traceability of the components.

The organisation shall provide a common work card or worksheet system to be used throughout relevant parts of the organisation. In addition, the organisation shall either transcribe accurately the maintenance data referred to in points (b) and (d) to such work cards or worksheets, or make precise reference to the particular maintenance task or tasks contained in that maintenance data. This applies to all of the following: 
(i) work cards or worksheets; 
(ii) computer-based systems; 
(iii) any other electronic data system. 
The organisation shall establish procedures to ensure that work cards, worksheets or other electronic data are available to the staff before the maintenance is performed.

When it is required to temporarily or permanently transfer maintenance tasks to another organisation, the organisation shall establish a procedure to ensure all of the following: 
1. all maintenance tasks are performed by organisations appropriately approved for their performance; 
2. the maintenance tasks are carried out in accordance with the maintenance data referred to in point 145.A.45; 
3. all necessary information for the performance of the maintenance tasks is made available to the organisation that performs them.

If specifically approved to do so for aircraft covered by Annex Vb (Part-ML), in accordance with point ML.A.903 of that Annex: 
1. perform airworthiness reviews; 
2. issue airworthiness review certificates; 
3. issue recommendations for the airworthiness review to the competent authority.
